{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:00:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:00:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18965"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18965"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.73,0.09,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11699"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5715"},{"type":"tags","id":"5718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27524"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EActive voluntary euthanasia refers to the deliberate administration of substances or performance of interventions with the primary intention of ending a person\u0027s life to relieve suffering. This practice remains a topic of significant ethical and legal debate in healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes active voluntary euthanasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cessation of mechanical ventilation","Withholding of artificial nutrition","Deliberate administration of lethal substances","Provision of pain relief that may hasten death","Withdrawal of life-sustaining treatment"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Edeliberate administration of lethal substances\u003C/strong\u003E. Active voluntary euthanasia involves taking specific actions intended to end a person\u0027s life, typically through the administration of medications or other substances that will cause death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithdrawal of life-sustaining treatment\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes passive euthanasia, where existing interventions are stopped but no active measures are taken to end life\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvision of pain relief that may hasten death\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the principle of double effect, where the primary intention is symptom relief rather than ending life\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithholding of artificial nutrition\u003C/strong\u003E - This is another form of passive euthanasia involving the decision not to initiate life-sustaining treatments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECessation of mechanical ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is also passive euthanasia, involving the withdrawal of artificial life support\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive voluntary euthanasia is distinct from other end-of-life practices because it involves taking deliberate actions with the primary intention of causing death, rather than allowing a natural death to occur or prioritising comfort care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active voluntary euthanasia involves deliberately taking actions to end a person\u0027s life to relieve suffering.","Active voluntary euthanasia differs from passive euthanasia which involves withdrawing or withholding life-sustaining treatment.","Active voluntary euthanasia is currently legal in only a few jurisdictions worldwide under strict conditions."],"references":["QUT. End of Life Law in Australia - Voluntary Assisted Dying. [online]. 2024. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://end-of-life.qut.edu.au/assisteddying","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","Euthanasia, human rights and the law. Australian Human Rights Commission. May 2016. Available at: https://humanrights.gov.au/our-work/age-discrimination/publications/euthanasia-human-rights-and-law#Heading95"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18965"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T14:24:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T14:24:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11699"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null